# git clone <url>

Clone: Get a copy of an existing Git repository.

✓ Creates a directory named repo_name  
✓ Initializes a .git directory inside the repository  
✓ Pulls down all the data  
✓ Checks out a working copy of the latest version

Transfer protocols: http, https, git, ssh

# cd path_to_git_repository
# touch file1 file2
# git status
On branch master
No commits yet
Untracked files:
  (use "git add <file>..." to include in what will be committed)
        file1
        file2
nothing added to commit but untracked files present (use "git add" to track)

✓ Track new files  
✓ Stage modified files

Examples:
- git add .       → Sign all files in the current directory as staged  
- git add file1   → Only file1 will be committed  
- git add *.c     → Only files ending in .c

✓ Commit all files that specified as staged by git add

git commit: It will open the default editor to enter the commit message.
(to change the default editor: git config --global core.editor)
-m : type commit message inline with the commit command
e.g: git commit -m "Update to v2.6.388 (HotFix)"

git status (modified and staged files !!!)

# cd path_to_git_repository
# echo "Hi" > file1
# git status

On branch master
Changes to be committed:
  (use "git reset HEAD <file>..." to unstage)
    modified:   file1

Changes not staged for commit:
  (use "git add <file>..." to update what will be committed)
  (use "git checkout -- <file>..." to discard changes in working directory)
    modified:   file1
